# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nixey-callahan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The 1894 baseball season was the Philadelphia Phillies' 12th season in the National League.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The team finished in fourth place with a record of 71–57, 18 games behind the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] In August 1894, the Phillies scored 312 runs, which still stands as the record in Major League Baseball for runs scored in a single month.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] Four of the team's outfielders hit over .400: Hall of Famers Sam Thompson, Ed Delehanty, and Billy Hamilton, plus reserve Tuck Turner.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies set the record for the highest team batting average for a single season, .349 according to Baseball Almanac or .350 according to Stathead.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] On August 6, 1894, at 11:00 AM, while the players were practicing at the ballpark, a fire broke out in the pavilion.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The players rushed to contain it but were quickly overwhelmed by the smoke.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] Within two hours, the fire had reduced the ballpark to charred wood and ashes.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The grandstand and bleachers of the original stadium were destroyed inflicting $80,000 in damages, equivalent to $2.98 million in 2025, which was covered fully by insurance.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The fire also spread to the adjoining properties, causing an additional $20,000 in damage, equivalent to $744,231 in 2025.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] While the Phillies were playing a short road trip and staging six home games at the University of Pennsylvania Grounds at 37th and Spruce, a building crew worked around the clock erecting temporary bleachers.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The makeshift stands were finished in time for the game on August 18.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] Following a fire which destroyed its ballpark on August 6, the Phillies played half a dozen home games at the University of Pennsylvania athletic field.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The team was especially productive there, winning five of its six games, and outscoring its opponents 93 to 35, including one game it won 29 to 4.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies returned to Broad and Huntington for the August 18, 1894 game against Cleveland rebuilt with new bleachers.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] 5,500 fans paid admission of which 4,000 were seated in left field.
[src:nixey-callahan/1894-philadelphia-phillies-season] The weather threatened rain otherwise a larger crowd would have been expected to see the Phillies win 11 to 6.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The **1897 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1897.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the Boston Beaneaters as the pennant winner of the National League and the Baltimore Orioles as runner-up.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The Orioles defeated the Beaneaters, four games to one, capturing their second consecutive Temple Cup.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] Due to lack of enthusiasm from both players and fans, and the perception that the Temple Cup was more of an exhibition contest than a true championship contest, the 1897 Temple Cup would be the final version of the championship series.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] Aside from the 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, this would be the last championship series until the birth of the modern World Series in 1903.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The 1897 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1893 and was the last season to use the format, which saw an extension of the schedule to 154 games the following season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring a game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Beaneaters.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 3, featuring four teams.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 11, with two exhibition games breaking up the series played on October 7–8 between Games 3 and 4.
[src:nixey-callahan/1897-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:nixey-callahan/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:nixey-callahan/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Though best known today by his childhood nickname "**Nixey**", in reality, he was seldom ever referred to by that name in contemporary sources during his playing days, as he instead preferred to go by Jimmy (or James) Callahan.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan was born in Fitchburg, Massachusetts on March 18, 1874.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] He played amateur baseball throughout Massachusetts.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan made his debut for the 1894 Philadelphia Phillies, the National League team run by Arthur Irwin.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan pitched in nine games that year, giving up more than an earned run per inning, so he was sent to the minor leagues for the 1895 season.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] He came back up to the major leagues in 1897 with the Chicago Cubs, where he stayed for four seasons.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] On September 20, 1902, Callahan pitched the first no-hitter in American League history.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Remarkably, only two years earlier, in the other extreme of his career, he had given up 48 hits in two consecutive starts in 1900, yielding 23 on September 11 and 25 in the game before.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan is also the only pitcher to have collected five hits in a game three times: June 29, 1897; May 18, 1902; and May 18, 1903.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan finished his major league career with 901 hits and 99 wins.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Since then, no player has matched both these numbers, although Babe Ruth came close.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Three nineteenth-century pitcher/infielders beat these numbers: John Montgomery Ward, Kid Gleason and Dave Foutz.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan managed the Chicago White Sox on two separate occasions and also managed the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan took a five-year break from playing in the American League to run his own semi-pro team, "Callahan's Logan Squares".
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] He said that he did this for financial reasons, but he returned when his team's attendances fell.
[src:nixey-callahan/nixey-callahan] Callahan died at age 60 in Boston on October 4, 1934.
